1 (3) For the office of state senator, member of the state board of
2 education or a candidate for local office whose jurisdiction has a
3 population that is 50,000 or more, $2,000 for each primary election, or
4 in lieu thereof, a caucus or convention of a political party.
5 (f) No expenditures made by a party committee in support of a
6 candidate, with or without such candidate's cooperation or consent, shall
7 constitute a contribution.
8 (f)(g) (1) If a candidate or a candidate's candidate committee
9 receives contributions prior to the date of the primary election and such
10 contributions are designated for use in connection with the general
11 election, such candidate or such committee shall use an acceptable
12 accounting method to distinguish between contributions received for the
13 primary election and contributions received for the general election.
14 Acceptable accounting methods include, but are not limited to:
15 (A) The designation of separate accounts for each election; or
16 (B) the establishment of separate books and records for each
17 election.
18 (2) Under any acceptable accounting method, the authorized records
19 of a candidate or candidate committee shall demonstrate that, prior to the
20 primary election, the recorded amount of cash on hand was at all times
21 equal to or in excess of an amount equal to the sum of the contributions
22 received and designated for use in connection with the general election
23 less the sum of disbursements made for the general election.
24 (g)(h) For purposes of this section, "jurisdiction" means:
25 (1) The city, county or school district if the candidate is seeking
26 election to a local office that is elected at large in such city, county or
27 school district; and
28 (2) the electoral district if the candidate is seeking election as a
29 member of a governing body that has member districts.
30 (h)(i) Any political funds which that have been collected and were
31 not subject to the reporting requirements of this act shall be deemed a
32 person subject to these contribution limitations.
33 (f)(i)(j) Any political funds which that have been collected and were
34 subject to the reporting requirements of the campaign finance act shall not
35 be used in or for the campaign of a candidate for a federal elective office.
36 (g) The amount contributed by each individual party committee of the
37 same political party other than a national party committee to any candidate
38 for office, for any primary election at which two or more candidates are
39 seeking the nomination of such party shall not exceed the following:
40 (1) For the pair of offices of governor and lieutenant governor and for
41 each of the other state officers elected from the state as a whole, $2,000 for
42 each primary election (or in lieu thereof a caucus or convention of a
43 political party).

